The function $f(x)$ consists of one function dividing another. This
means we should use the quotient rule to find the derivative.

Changing $\sqrt{x}$ to $x^{\frac12}$, and applying the quotient rule we
get:

\begin{align*}
f'(x) & = \frac{(x^{\frac12} )'\cos x - x^{\frac12}(\cos x)'}{\cos^2 x} \\
 & = \frac{\frac12x^{-\frac12}\cos x - x^{\frac12}(-\sin x)}{\cos^2 x} \\
 & = \frac{\frac{\cos x}{2\sqrt{x}} + \sqrt{x}\sin x}{\cos^2 x}
\end{align*}

This answer is sufficient, however, we can simplify this term by
multiplying the numerator and the denominator by $2\sqrt{x}$ to get

\begin{align*}
= \frac{\cos x+ 2x \sin x}{2\sqrt{x} \cos^2 x}
\end{align*}
